            "answer_text": "The dominant reversible reaction with water is: CO3 (2-) + H2O \u21cc HCO3 (1-) + OH (1-) Further reaction of the HCO3 (1-) ion with H2O would be negligible. Na (1+) ions have no chemical reaction with water, though oxygen atoms in H2O molecules will be attracted around sodium ions. I do not really agree with Rajeev's formulation. If any carbonic acid H2CO3 (fizzy water essentially) were formed it would decompose to H2O and CO2 and then you would end up with a sodium hydroxide solution, but this does not happen. ",
